      "Which of the following statements is/are correct?\n\n1. Radical action can also be attributed to mild surrender where one acts against societal expectations.\n2. Submitting to one's limitations, given the effect of age and other factors, ought not to be conflated with laziness.\n3. 'Leading man' usually refers to one who plays the lead role in a movie; in this instance the implication is that Hugh Grant is performing the role of not an action hero, but that of a resting one!\n\nSelect the answer using the code given below.",
    options: [
      { id: "A", text: "1, 2 and 3" },
      { id: "B", text: "1 and 2 only" },
      { id: "C", text: "2 and 3 only" },
      { id: "D", text: "1 only" },
    ],
    correctOption: "A",
    explanation:
      "Statement 1 is CORRECT: The passage calls Grant's act of napping 'something quietly radical.' Napping in a public, formal setting is a 'mild surrender' to the body's needs, yet it is described as radical because it goes against 'society's relentless performance metrics.' Acting against societal expectations through quiet surrender is the core theme of the passage - Statement 1 is valid. Statement 2 is CORRECT: The passage says Grant made 'an elegant case for surrender. Not to laziness, but to limits.' The passage explicitly distinguishes between surrendering to one's physical limits (e.g., age) and laziness. Statement 2 correctly captures this distinction. Statement 3 is CORRECT: The passage ends with 'The perpetually sleep-deprived discovered a leading man, not of action, but of rest.' 'Leading man' is a film term for the main actor (usually the action hero). The passage uses it to imply Grant is now playing a different kind of lead role - one of rest rather than action. This is a deliberate play on words, and Statement 3 accurately captures this wordplay.",
